%N A390046 Circular sorting numbers: a(n) = maximum number of swaps required to arrange n labeled points on a circle into clockwise order.
%C A390046 Arrange n distinct labels 0,..,n-1 clockwise around a circle. A swap exchanges the labels on two positions of the circle. Then a(n) is the maximum, over all starting arrangements, of the minimum number of swaps required to reach the clockwise order 0,1,..,n-1 (up to rotation).
%C A390046 In terms of permutations of Z_n (the integers mod n), we have
%C A390046 a(n) = max_{pi in S(Z_n)} (n - max_{k in Z_n} cyc(x -> pi(x + k))), where cyc(sigma) is the number of cycles of the permutation sigma.
%C A390046 In terms of the Cayley graph of S_n generated by all transpositions, a(n) is the maximum distance to the subgroup generated by the n-cycle (1 2 .. n).
%C A390046 Introduced in "Circular sorting" (Adin, Alon, Roichman, 2025) and further studied in "Circular sorting, strong complete mappings and wreath product constructions (Bastide, Bishnoi, Groenland, Gijswijt, Joshi, 2025).
%C A390046 The upper bound a(n)<=n-2 is known to hold with equality for n=p and n=3p, where p is a prime number. Other known values are: a(25)=22, a(27)=24.
%C A390046 A permutation pi in S(Z_n) achieving the bound n-2 (optimal permutation) is necessarily a strong complete mapping of Z_n (see A071607).
%C A390046 For primes p<=19 all optimal permutations are affine. For certain primes p>=23, optimal permutations exist that are quadratic orthomorphisms (see A390047).
%C A390046 For all composite n<=21 we have a(n)=n-3. It is unknown if this is true for all composite n, the smallest open case being n=22.
%H A390046 Ron M. Adin, Noga Alon, and Yuval Roichman, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.14398">Circular sorting</a>, arXiv:2502.14398 [math.CO], 2025.
%H A390046 Paul Bastide, Anurag Bishnoi, Carla Groenland, Dion Gijswijt, and Rohinee Joshi, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2510.18529">Circular sorting, strong complete mappings and wreath product constructions</a>, arXiv:2510.18529 [math.CO], 2025.
%F A390046 a(n) = max_{pi in S_n} min_{k = 0..n-1} cyc(x -> pi(x + k mod n)), where cyc(sigma) is the number of cycles of permutation sigma.
%e A390046 For n = 6, consider the clockwise order 0,3,5,1,2,4.
%e A390046 Swapping 0<->5, then 3<->4, then 4<->5 yields 4,5,0,1,2,3, a rotation of 0,1,2,3,4,5.
%e A390046 Hence the labels are in clockwise order after 3 swaps.
%e A390046 The same cannot be achieved with only 2 swaps, so a(6) >= 3.
%e A390046 Every other starting arrangement can be sorted in 3 or fewer swaps, so a(6) = 3.
%o A390046 (Python)
%o A390046 from itertools import permutations
%o A390046 def a(n):
%o A390046    def cyc(f):
%o A390046       seen=[False]*n; c=0
%o A390046       for x in range(n):
%o A390046          if not seen[x]:
%o A390046             c+=1; y=x
%o A390046             while not seen[y]: seen[y]=True; y=f[y]
%o A390046       return c
%o A390046    best=0
%o A390046    for pi in permutations(range(n)):
%o A390046       mx=0
%o A390046       for k in range(n):
%o A390046          f = [pi[(x+k)%n] for x in range(n)]
%o A390046          mx=max(mx,cyc(f))
%o A390046       best=max(best, n-mx)
%o A390046    return best
